column2: an organisation that fights for the rights of survivors of sexual assault

column1: 106156;instagram;2018-12-20 04:49:42;FALSE;"even when i think i'm happy my heart starts to sink. i worry that the love of my life is going to leave me or entertain another female. how am i worthy of anything? i'm constantly in fear that a happy life will be interrupted by sadness. so far this has been true. i have never experienced constant happiness. every time i let my guard down something happens. i'm terribly depressed right now and i dont know what to do. i need to go to a therapist again but how do i even set that up. my insurance is through my parents. i cant tell them i'm bad again. they think i've been good for years and that's a lie. i just want to be happy but my heart is too heavy. evey time a car drives in front of me i just want to walk out and die. why dont i? because then my death will be on that person and that's not okay.

column1: 106158;instagram;2018-12-20 04:51:18;FALSE;"i am a normal middle-class girl and didn't have family or godfathers when i started my career. post my father’s death
column2: my mother at the age of 50
column3: started to work along with her four children
column4: me and my three siblings. we were all starting out in life then. two years after my father died
column5: i set up my own production house.

column2: i produced and wrote the hit tv show
column3: tara. when the lead actor alok nath started harassing my lead actress
column4: we decided to let go of him. a year later
column5: we were asked to change our script to bring back alok nath while letting go of our lead actress. because everything including my four other shows was at stake
column7: we were asked to pull the plug on all the shows.

column2: i was at alok nath’s house party. during the evening
column3: i felt like my drinks were spiked. i decided to leave. i walked out late in the night and alok nath came behind and dropped me home. and the next thing was that i was brutalised in my own house.

column2: i got a job to write and direct a series for another production house. alok nath managed to find his way into that too. i resigned from directing and continued to write the series. i didn’t want to be anywhere around him. but when he asked me to come to his house
column3: i went. i needed my job and the the money. but soon after this incident

column2: but when i went to pitch i would be nervous. to deal with all the fear
column3: i began to drink a lot. i flirted with drugs but couldn't find any solution in it. i had lost my bearings.

column2: there was outrage against bullying all around. i decided to come out with my story. today
column3: cintaa has finally expelled alok nath and for me it was punishment delivered after 19 years. i still had to file an official complaint against alok nath
column4: which was later converted to an fir by the mumbai police.

column1: i loved my life. i was a successful woman. i was a party person. i was liberated and empowered. but none of it meant that i was available for what i didn't want.
i began telling this story because the most sanskaari man on tv owes me and the other women an apology.

column1: 🤬🙅‍♀️😡my month has been marked by reading about women and their anger and how they have historically and are increasingly wielding that rage in politics and society. @sorayachemaly’s #ragebecomesher is a nice companion piece to rebecca traister’s #goodandmad and rebecca solnit’s “men explain things to me.” taken together
column2: with some examples and anecdotes described by three different women
column3: we’re able to arrive at a fuller picture of why women are angry
column5: and how they can channel it and are channeling it in constructive ways. chemaly’s book is a bit more academic than traister’s. she references many studies and is more interested in the psychology of anger and how so much develops in the childhood and upbringing of girls. chemaly shares stories from her own life
column6: and the ones about parenting her daughter are especially poignant because you get a real sense that the way we treat boys and girls differently is a hard thing to overcome - it is so deeply engrained that even someone who has spent so much of her life studying this disparity and its deleterious effects on women and society can still fall into its traps. i’m glad chemaly wrote rage becomes her and i’m glad i read it. #goodreads #reading #igreads #bookstagram #bookstagrammer #instabooks #instabook #igbook #igbookreview #igbooks #igreaders #read #book #books #womensmarch #anger #women #feminism #igfeminist #activism #metoo #pinkwave";en;#Repost

column1: 106197;instagram;2018-12-20 03:40:11;FALSE;"""it’s completely valid to still feel love for someone with whom we’ve invested so much time and energy into building a relationship.
even after the abusive behaviors begin
column2: we know leaning into these feelings of love

column1: 106213;instagram;2018-09-29 21:40:13;FALSE;"i am an overcomer of sexual abuse. many of you know my story. many of you know what my family has been through. the very person who should have loved and protected me became my personal monster. i know everything happening has been setting off alot of triggers for people and i'm finding more and more of the people i care about have been sexually assaulted and i had no idea. i know what it feels like to not be believed
column3: to have my attacker supported over me
column4: the crushing feeling of shame and worthlessness
column5: and feeling completely and utterly alone. i was fortunate enough to have the court take my side but i can't even imagine what dr. ford must be feeling. she's not even getting a trail. she's just speaking up against this disgusting man saying that he shouldn't have one of the highest forms of political power and yet she is being persecuted for speaking her truth and her character is being assassinated. column1: i’ve been mostly taking on only light reading (actual light
column2: not hermione light) for the past few weeks given it’s the end of a long year and i’m still trying to hit 100 books. but for some reason i decided now would be a good time to reflect on all the anger i and most all other women i know have felt for the past two years
column3: flying in the face of the fluffy reading i’ve been craving. and yet
column4: i was thrilled to be reading rebecca traister again. she’s one of my favorite writers for her ability to tackle intangible ideas (like voluntary spinsterhood) and communicate them in such punchy
column5: effortless writing. and of course it was impossible not to compare this book to her modern classic

column1: with that book i felt like she was on to something that few had either not yet recognized or didn’t dare to point out. women don’t need to be married! here’s what they’re doing instead
column2: isn’t this exciting! in good and mad on the flip side
column3: if you’ve been conscious for the past two years
column4: this book might feel like adding salt to an open wound. her analysis here is ripped from the headlines of 2016-18 in such a way that makes it impossible not to nod along and think yup
column5: that feels like a hundred years ago now

column1: while it’s nice to have the insight that traister brings to this moment
column2: more than anything i could see this being required reading in future history classes (if there is a future where women’s history is taught). most of all
column3: i loved the resounding message of the book: that to be angry is to be smart
column5: and hopeful. that this moment—of protests
column7: of #metoo—is part of a larger history

column1: two months after lisa gray divorced her ex-husband
column2: she discovered that he had been sexually abusing her daughter nikki throughout their seven-year marriage. the abuse started when nikki was in third grade and continued until she was 15-years-old. with her best friend’s encouragement
column3: nikki told her mother about her step-father’s abuse after he moved out of their house. lisa was shocked and ashamed to learn of the abuse. “as it started to settle in
column4: i replayed it in my mind. how could this happen? i had so much shame
column5: so much guilt that i had brought this man into my house to molest my child. what kind of mother am i? the guilt and the shame were deafening—but at the same time i knew i had to do what was necessary for my daughter.”

column1: nikki felt ashamed because she believed she should have stopped the abuse earlier
column2: but lisa told her that it was not her fault. “i had talked to my children about stranger danger
column3: but never had conversations about what happens if you have to have dinner every night with the person abusing you.” lisa and nikki had a close relationship
column4: so after learning of the abuse
column5: lisa was confused about why nikki hadn’t disclosed earlier. when the abuse started
column6: nikki was too young to understand what was happening. as nikki got older
column7: the shame and humiliation she felt prevented her from disclosing. she was also trying to protect her mother.

column1: they chose to report the abuse and found the local police helpful throughout the process. the case went to court
column2: which became a year-long process that was extremely difficult for nikki. lisa notes the lengthy criminal trial process and how frustrating it can be for survivors at a time when they’re already vulnerable. “once they’ve reached that spot where they’re willing to go public
column3: they want something to be done. it seems to take an eternity.” another issue with the length of many sexual abuse criminal trials is that the perpetrator may have the opportunity to continue to abuse other victims.

column1: 106280;instagram;2018-12-20 01:59:00;FALSE;"#recoverymoment: it was around this time last year when i and so many other amazing people took up the #metoo movement. sharing my very personal stories around #sexualassault on a platform like @buzzfeed felt unreal
column3: and so intensely validating. it was an experience that helped me further my healing and recognize my worth. but something i didn't talk about much was how my trauma acutely impacted my eating disorder tendencies for months perhaps even into the spring season. i couldn't eat
column5: or focus. i lost my appetite. involuntary bodily functions (i.e. urinating) disgusted me. i wanted to have perfect control over every aspect of my life.

column2: after being sidelined by an injury and focusing on easing myself back into a movement practice i enjoy
column5: and more easily tired out. and i **am** all of these three things. but i can say that i love myself more
column6: and that i see my body less as a burden and more as beautiful evidence of my resilience and survival. i weighed in (out of habit) at my heaviest weight yet the other day
column7: and i realized that for the first time
column8: i feel okay. i feel okay with this softness
column9: okay with not being at my peak performance level
column10: okay with all of these things. i am not in control. and i am okay.";;en;#RECOVERYMOMENT:

column1: 106304;instagram;2018-12-20 00:55:19;FALSE;"@brenebrown is one of my most inspirational authors; one i always come back to. her talk on the power of vulnerability opened my eyes to the walls
column2: and heavy barriers i had created around myself.

column3: come from my past experiences. no one had to ask me to start building them. it came easy. start with an alcoholic father who left when i was born
column4: my stepfather who assured us we would never be good enough and abandoned us by ten
column7: exhausting coming of age first love that brought out the worst of both of us. no one had to lay down the ground work
column8: my walls were up and no one was getting through.

column1: and it would be easy to keep them high and mighty. but
column2: i have now noticed that it gets lonely inside these walls. and more importantly realize
column3: that i don't want to breed that behavior. our most vulnerable selves allow us to see what light we truly carry; who we truly are. and through that light we find light in others
column4: and through that we celebrate love. and who doesnt want to be loved and share love? because isn't it the epitomy of all that we need more of in this world?

column2: thank you brenee brown for taking a stand and breaking down your walls
column3: to allow us to see the magic in working through our own.

column1: 106328;instagram;2018-12-20 01:15:48;FALSE;"**long post alert** ☘i think its worth the read though☘
i'm a diablo & coconut sandwich....there isn't any place i'd rather be than nuzzled up with these two gentle giants....
if you asked me 6 months ago
column2: hell~just 3 months ago that this is what i'd be doing come october....i'd laugh and ask what you been smoking 😂😂😂 now
column3: all i can say is wow! i am deeply
column4: humbly & gratefully blessed to have the honor of being given the responsibility of taking care of these horses...these empathic

column3: a traumatic brain injury survivor (with permanent damage)
column4: a domestic violence/ sexual assual survivor and i've fought hard battles with my addiction throughout the years....before october
column5: i had just been settling with the life i had.

column2: i completely & thoroughly understand the true meaning (because i am living it) the soul deep experience and feelings of what it means to live a ""life second to none"" the way it is referred to in the ""big ""book"". never did i think i was capable of attaining that type of life...until now!  throughout the years
column3: i never lost hope that tomorrow will be better""~every day~ and that kept me going one day at a time...

column1: my hope in better tomorrows led to the life i live today and it just happened
column2: fell in my lap as you say...i love these horses more than i thought possible.... and for me
column3: a more powerful wow factor ~ i'm moving to 37 acres of rolling horse property in ashburn
column4: ga that will also add an additional 5 horses to our already family of 8!

frolicking and running free along the countryside. that's what i'm going to wake up to every morning and be able watch from my front porch as the sunsets every night.... if that isn't a ""life second to none"" then i damn sure dont know what is....it's is my ""life second to none"" and i deserve every bit of serenity
column7: light and love that  this life brings to me!

column2: my name is desiree. i am a sexual assault survivor. i am a college student majoring in anthropology. i am an intersectional activist & a sexual assault survivor advocate. i identify as she/her/hers and i am afro-indigenous-latina. i am almost 30 years young. i am making moves to do big things like helping to make campuses safer & spreading awareness about #mmiw
column3: starting locally. i am currently organizing & speaking at a womxns march where i will speak up for those who are victims and survivors of sexual violence. i have recently reached a goal in my own pursuit of justice for the violence i endured years ago. i couldn’t of done it without you all. i love you all and you are the reason i am alive & here & still fighting
column6: & being my best self. @desiree.nicki is my page and i will be creating this space for activism

column1: 106334;instagram;2018-12-20 00:00:04;FALSE;"well today was one of those not so good very bad days. in hindsight it all started yesterday with an impromptu mandatory meeting at work in which one of my coworkers attempted to head off the news that was about to me released in local media
column2: that her husband stands accused of sexual assault by five different women. though i have much compassion for her and all parties involved in this all around horrible situation
column3: as a #metoo survivor some of her comments about the accusers was very triggering to me. and thus a slow
column4: downward spiral into sadness and anger started brewing within me following this meeting. i would have (should have) stayed home from work today had i felt it was an option for me. i’ll spare the gory details
column5: but my day included me angrily smashing a water bottle in the parking lot at the end of my not stellar day
column6: someone witnessed my childish tirade and says i did this in the building managers office... so yep. i take responsibility for my actions but ugh
column7: just want to cry about it all for now.

column1: at least in my reading i received all of my favorites: the black madonna
column2: baby jesus himself (plus isis is discussed in the book) and mother mary. the ix vessels plus a ace and ii of holy rood to remind me that everything is cyclical and a new direction is always available if i am willing to take the steps. and mother mary on the vii distaff to remind me that seeing myself as a victim is not going to serve me very well.
i guess whether thought i needed it or not
column3: another layer of healing is required. i hate that the grief of experiences long ago can still overpower my good senses on occasion and i just rage. “i thought i was way past this!” yet i will keep on keeping on. #tomorrowisanewday

column1: thank you for listening. be blessed

column1: as i looked down the sidewalk
column2: i noticed a well-to-do looking woman walking toward me.⠀

column1: as she reached the intersection a block ahead
column2: she crossed the street. then she continued to walk in the same direction. i assumed she lived on that side of the street. at the end of the block
column3: i glanced back. once past me
column4: she crossed back to my side of the street and continued on her way.⠀

column1: 106369;instagram;2018-12-18 22:18:27;FALSE;"2018 has been a challenge to say the least. it started with the scariest health situation i’ve ever been in. quickly followed up with the most traumatic heartbreak i’ve ever experienced. then i lost confidence in my career. #fuck

2018 has been a struggle to stay afloat- alone. i didn’t know which way was up or how to get out of my severely violent depression. i kept myself numb with booze and drugs. i lied to myself that i was totes ok.

column2: in secret. i fucken hated everyone around me. i hated them for being there but not seeing how much i was hurting myself. i hated myself for being weak. i attempted to end the madness but when i woke up 3 days later
column3: ironically it was my birthday. that night
column4: i left seattle with zero intentions of ever returning. since then
column5: i’ve spent months in recovery trying to understand what my purpose is. clearly

column1: my family had no idea what was going on. as it turns out i’m a better liar than i ever gave myself credit for. i decided to be the most impulsive i’ve ever been because i don’t trust myself anymore. it’s been a battle to keep myself from driving a little too fast on rainy days
column2: to not walk down sketchy parts of random cities alone at night
column3: to not experiment with chemical cocktails.

column1: i found temporary bandages in men
column2: which i don’t regret. i never needed a man’s validation. but god damn
column3: i’m a sucker for an alpha’s attention. #fuckyoumooney

column1: as dark as it has been
column2: i’m proud of the few things i’ve done in hopes of recalibrating my head and heart. i finally drove from coast to coast
column3: something i’ve wanted to do for years. i dreamt of seeing noelani’s face light up if i were to surprise her at school one day. i spent significant time with my parents which was long overdue. i went for motorcycle rides with my big brothers and i finally got to indulge in all the donuts with my sister without giving a shit about getting fat.

column1: what i’ve learned because of all this
column2: is that i’m actually legit #fearless. but the real lesson is that i’m not done here yet. come on 2019! i’m fucken ready. #todayistheday #burnittotheground #dobetter #bebetter #stayalive #fuckenthrive #pitterpatter #thatfadetho";;en;#fuck

column3: something i’ve wanted to do for years. i dreamt of seeing noelani’s face light up if i were to surprise her at school one day. i spent significan not time with my parents which was long overdue. i went for motorcycle rides with my big brothers and i finally got to indulge in all the donuts with my sister without giving a shit about getting fat.

column1: what i’ve learned because of all this
column2: is that i’m actually legit #fearless. but the real lesson is that i’m not done here yet. come on 2019! i’m fucken ready. #todayistheday #burnittotheground #dobetter #bebetter #stayalive #fuckenthrive #pitterpatter #thatfadetho";"2018 has been a challenge to say the least. it staed with the scariest health situation i’ve ever been in. quickly followed up with the most traumatic heabreak i’ve ever experienced. then i lost confidence in my career.

column1: 2018 has been a struggle to stay afloat- alone. i didn’t know which way was up or how to get out of my severely violent depression. i kept myself numb with booze and drugs. i lied to myself that i was totes ok.

column2: in secret. i fucken hated everyone around me. i hated them for being there but not seeing how much i was huing myself. i hated myself for being weak. i attempted to end the madness but when i woke up 3 days later
column3: ironically it was my bihday. that night
column4: i left seattle with zero intentions of ever returning. since then
column5: i’ve spent months in recovery trying to understand what my purpose is. clearly

column1: my family had no idea what was going on. as it turns out i’m a better liar than i ever gave myself credit for. i decided to be the most impulsive i’ve ever been because i don’t trust myself anymore. it’s been a battle to keep myself from driving a little too fast on rainy days
column2: to not walk down sketchy pas of random cities alone at night
column3: to not experiment with chemical cocktails.

column1: i found temporary bandages in men
column2: which i don’t regret. i never needed a man’s validation. but god damn
column3: i’m a sucker for an alpha’s attention. uckyoumooney

column1: 106425;instagram;2018-12-19 22:37:11;FALSE;"i made this print about a year ago.

i think society has really accepted the concept that boys will be boys. i have been assaulted and harrased many times. and over the years i have just become more aggressive towards those who seem like they might want to harm me. or ideally i would be. i did a study abroad in italy and was sexually assaulted it had been one of the most difficult things for me to move forward from. i felt alone. i had very few friends and no family around me during my abroad. i was in a place i have never been. i was scared and i felt stupid but i did what i though best and reported the incident. he got fired but nothing else happened. i am glad for what little i could do. i have learned a lot about myself from that situation. and making art and talking about it helped me a lot. i made a lot of work addressing my assault
column2: this is one of them. i haven't been very open about my assault on social media. it's not something i think warrants a post but i am glad to share this with you all and i hope it gives you strength.

column1: this art piece speaks so deeply to me. being kept close and 'protected' yet being physically and emotionally harmed and controlled by a demon. he controlled my mind and my body
column2: but never my heart. i lost all sense of control faster than i realized it was happening. i lost all sense of myself and my well being and i got consumed by something more powerful than myself. i lost myself and most of my loved ones.

column1: i always said ""that would never happen to me"" until it did. i missed the warning signs. i missed my window to escape. i got sucked in so fast and it all happened in a blink of an eye.
i look back on messages with friends back then and see the cries for help. but no one ever really knew until the end. when i finally got away. breaking free was the hardest
column2: yet most rewarding thing i have ever done.
i'm bullied by people who chose to believe the demon over the girl
column3: but he knows and i know what really happened. you don't. everyone has a different story. i have all the painful memories
column6: emotional photos. i will never forget what i went through. but i will be damned to ever go through it again.

column1: this is the press release that we decided to publicly have on april 18
column2: 2018 detailing the events of nadia’s murder. we decided to make things public to be able to bring awareness of the rise of domestic abuse in calgary. the cps had received around 18 000 calls in 2017
column3: mostly from neighbours or the community.  it is important to report incidences and be aware of people in your neighbourhood
column4: and if you hear any commotions
column5: to call the police. this is a community issue and to bring that awareness and have a safe and empathetic environment for those who do decide to seek help or come out as a survivor. by doing that we need to talk about those issues and break the stigma that our culture has and those of minorities. thank you for your support ❤️❤️ #domesticviolence #abuse #narcissisticabuse #gaslighting #sociopath #mentalhealth #domesticabuse #emotionalabuse #trauma #verbalabuse #domesticviolenceawareness #psychologicalabuse #mentalhealthawareness #stoptheviolence #survivor #metoo #sexualabuse #divorce #toxicpeople #suicideprevention #endthestigma #suicideawareness #stopthestigma #suicidesurvivor #liars #yyc #calgary #canada";;en;#domesticviolence

column3: here to talk about women. there’s a quote
column5: that i am obsessed with lately… “when a woman conceives her true self
column6: a miracle occurs and life around her begins again.” i can vouch for that quote. has self portraiture solved all my issues? no.. they still hang on me like a monkey on my back. but i see me now
column7: more clearly than i ever have in my 48 years around the sun… and i want to do more. - -

column1: there’s no shortage of conversation around women these days. the rise up of the #metoo or #timesup movement invariably contributes to my thoughts on this subject. as layers of my own issues are peeled away through self portraiture
column2: i am continually reminded how hard it is to be seen. we show and hide what we want
column4: and sometimes even self edit to “fit in” with how society expects us to. there’s fear and shame
column5: image and struggle… and i want to do more. i want to contribute somehow to the narrative and provide a space where women can “let go”. one of the first things women say is “i’m scared to do this
column6: but feel i must!” and i say yes.. let’s be vulnerable together! - -

column1: as i move into 2019 it is a certainty that photographing women is top of my list because i “have” to do more. i “have” to contribute to the narrative and provide a space where women can let go and lift the veil.. maybe permanently. - -

;el mayor drama de las cifras de abuso sexual infantil que publicamos desde la es que estas son apenas la cúspide del problema . es la mínima expresión de los casos en los que `` todo procede '' . debajo de esta cifra hay un inmenso vacío de abusos perpetrados en los que se ha aprehendido al agresor , denuncias abandonadas que avanzaron por falta de pruebas , familias que nunca denunciaron , familias que nunca le creyeron las víctimas , víctimas que nunca revelaron lo que les ocurrió lo que les está ocurriendo . ayer el ministerio público venezolano anunció las cifras de denuncias recibidas por abuso sexual en este último año ( un poco más ) . pero esos números aún dejan un impoante número de víctimas agresores sexuales en la oscuridad del desconocimiento . de acuerdo save children ( 2001 ) apenas el 10 % de los casos llega ser denunciado , lamentablemente en consideramos que aún estamos lejos de estimar correctamente las dimensiones de esta tragedia . `` sin detección es posible implementar medidas de protección , ni brindar tratamiento para las víctimas sus familias . al mismo tiempo , debemos considerar que el agresor sexual que reconoce su crimen , que busca tratamiento , que es identificado ni recibe sanción alguna representa un riesgo para los niños para toda la sociedad . column2: just part of the story we are all interacting with.

column1: the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters
column2: then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

column3: and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters
column4: so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

column1: 106685;instagram;2018-12-19 17:29:12;FALSE;"okay i gotta weigh in on this whole “baby it’s cold outside” fiasco. i used to have a little holiday rant about this song and it’s seemingly coercive lyrics - i was a little indignant that it seemed like nobody heard this side of the lyric. but then
column3: in the middle of #metoo and a breakthrough year of awareness
column4: i was asked  to sing the song with a beloved bandleader. i thought “oh no...” but then spent some time with the song and the lyrics. it’s full of fun innuendo
column5: it’s a song about adults with mutual desire and if anything
column6: a punitive and puritanical society that tries to thwart them(or can be conveniently referenced in order to defer a pleasure.) i have come to the new belief that this is truly a grown folks song
column7: and that if it’s rendered by the performers without a tongue firmly planted in cheek and a wink in the eye
column8: it can be mistakes for something ominous (which it’s not.) it’s dated
column9: and maybe needs to be rethought by those that sing it a little more carefully and treated with more dimension than it has....

column1: do you have any favorite fun contemporary christmas songs? i feel like for as much time as i’ve spent analyzing this i could have found a few more tunes that are underrepresented now! #babyitscoldoutside";;en;#Metoo
column2: #babyitscoldoutside;;;;;0;;klsergeant;Kristen Lee Sergeant;;0;False;6;0;0;69;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/8f7375207d62357096dc9fef30f81fbf/5D06A8C0/t51.2885-15/e35/46604609_2352077555078731_5199180328726192201_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"okay i gotta weigh in on this whole “baby it’s cold outside” fiasco. i used to have a little holiday rant about this song and it’s seemingly coercive lyrics - i was a little indigt that it seemed like nobody heard this side of the lyric. but then
column4: in the middle of #metoo and a breakthrough year of awareness
column5: i was asked  to sing the song with a beloved bandleader. i thought “oh no...” but then spent some time with the song and the lyrics. it’s full of fun innuendo
column6: it’s a song about adults with mutual desire and if anything
column7: a punitive and puritanical society that tries to thwart them(or can be conveniently referenced in order to defer a pleasure.) i have come to the new belief that this is truly a grown folks song
column8: and that if it’s rendered by the performers without a tongue firmly planted in cheek and a wink in the eye
column9: it can be mistakes for something ominous (which it’s not.) it’s dated
column10: and maybe needs to be rethought by those that sing it a little more carefully and treated with more dimension than it has....

column1: 106687;instagram;2018-12-19 17:29:40;FALSE;"it was great to see you again @fayedorcas ! you are definitely one of the bravest women i've ever met! speaking out is hard but starting a #metoo campaign towards an organization that you once loved is extremely hard. you are being a great example for all women! #support #metoomovement #breakthrough
感謝您參與聯署并留下聯繫方式！本次聯署行動總共收集到1128人聯署，加上聯合發起人總共1251個簽署單位。

然而，突破及突破匯動（以下合稱突破）卻一直對我們的訴求冷處理。11月初，我們通過盧龍光牧師中間協調，嘗試促成與突破的半公開會面，商討訴求的具體實施步驟與標準。協調至中途，突破突然單方面落閘，拒絕會面，并且沒有給出合理的解釋。11月13日，我們再次向基督教協進會遞交書面申請，邀請協進會作為第三方平台協調促成會面。協進會方面向突破前後發送了兩次官方聯絡函，至今已過去超過一個月，仍未收到突破方面的確切回應。
因此，我們計劃於12月20日（週四）上午11:00am前往突破青年村以報佳音的方式公開遞信，先誠邀各位聯署人與我們同行。行動具體信息如下：
集合：10:40am於沙田鐵路站出閘口7-11集合，再一齊坐67k小巴/的士上突破青年村
道具：我們會準備4-5塊手持標語牌以及若干聖誕道具，也歡迎您自帶標語牌和道具
歌單：我們會預先根據報名人數影印，當天集合時派發
2. angels we have heard on high
3. go tell it on the mountain
10. 青年向上歌（請將歌詞中的“我”替換成“你”） 報名鏈接：https://goo.gl/forms/jngq6uzlgcuzz5h92
若您將與我們同去，敬請進入以上網頁登記報名。再次感謝您的關心與支持！

column1: scar tissue is my way of shining a light at what's been kept in the dark for so long. in the fall of 2017
column2: a seismic shift happened in our social consciousness. as i scrolled through my social media
column3: a hashtag kept popping up over and over again: #metoo. women from all different points of my life (and even some men) began posting this phrase
column5: some posting detailed descriptions of their specific #metoo moment. it happened to me. it happened to my best friends. it happened to my mother. it happened to my teacher from elementary school. it happened to so many of us. for so many years i viewed rape and sexual assault as many others did. it is a strange villain twirling his mustache and waiting down a dark alleyway to pounce on some poor
column6: innocent young woman he didn’t know. but it isn’t that black and white. it’s a sad
column8: and daunting spectrum of gray. that’s where it lives and that’s what makes scar tissue so important.""

column1: 106756;instagram;2018-12-19 17:12:00;FALSE;"i was a young mum and came home to a new baby who rarely slept erin hendra!
i had no family support save for the first 2 days and was fairly cluless.
i was shy and struggled with confidence meaning that i was petrified about going to mums groups so suffered alone with post natal depression.
i self managed it and taught myself to parent to the best of my ability.
i knew what sort of mum i wanted to be and muddled through.
fast forward 6 years and i was blessed to be given 6 children under 8 to love and cherish.

i was equally stressed and was often found locked in the bathroom whilst chaos ensued outside the door with cries of 'wipe my bum' 'i need a drink' 'he hit me' and other such delights which seemed to be played on a continuous loop!! i had no idea where to go for support and got through with the help and humour of jenny harper trudy ferreira and hannah finch.
without these folks i would be eternally destined to basket weaving!
this is why today having passed my interview i have commited to becoming a home start volunteer for 2 hours a week.

column3: practical help and nurturing to families who are where i was all those years ago.

column1: it's only 2 hours a week and is a chance for me to give back at a time in my life when i am focusing so much on giving back to others and leaving my mark on the world through contributing.

column1: i grew up envying famous people. if you were famous
column2: then you were rich. and if you were rich
column3: then you had more comfort.  on top of all the perks that lazy people like myself drool over
column4: they could use their recognition to influence others to act. you see many celebrities today taking ownership to a cause like the #metoo movement or #blacklivesmatter. i trained myself to believe that in order to get to the point where i can use my voice to influence others
column5: i had to be famous enough.

column3: and i am reminded of jesus' birth. the messiah that came into the world to save mankind from eternal destruction was born inconspicuously. the one that was soon to die for our sins
column4: conquer death and rise with all power in his hands was not necessarily famous enough.

column1: i am trusting on god to use me to influence those around me as he chooses. he already established my identity in the beginning. i don't have to reach some level of fame or notoriety for god to use me. if i believe that god is ultimately in control
column2: i must also trust his timing and declaration of things.

column1: why believing sexual violence survivors is evidence-based (and important!)
sexual violence — defined as any sexual act committed against someone without that individual’s freely-given consent — is a critical social problem; one that social movements including #notokay
column3: and #timesup have recently brought to the forefront of media discourse surrounding violence

column1: according to the centers for disease control and prevention
column2: about 1 in 3 women and nearly 1 in 6 men are victims of contact sexual violence in their lifetime
column3: with over 40% of women victims and about a quarter of men victims experiencing their first completed rape before the age of 18.

column7: and genderfluid youth are at even higher risk for experiencing sexual violence; 46% of bisexual women and 47% of transgender people are sexually assaulted at some point in their lifetime
column8: and trans women of color are widely regarded as being at the highest risk for experiencing sexual violence.

column1: 106846;instagram;2018-12-19 15:13:06;FALSE;"for me one of the most important thing i have done for my health and wellness is stop online dating and this article explains why it was necessary.
i resisted online dating for a few years after my divorce but i work from home in a small city so it is challenging to meet single men so eventually i gave in.
at first it was incredibly awkward and really never got easier so i would always be drinking on these dates to ease anxiety. the apps are addictive
column2: the alcohol was addictive and nothing good ever came from this combination. my life is so much better without dealing with dating. i really was seeing no benefit as men always liked to tell me that i was not good enough
column3: thin enough and didn't have children so therefore they were going to look for someone better. they were always begging for pics though? it's hard to understand but online dating makes no sense. eventually my brother told me the truth
column4: most men have no interest in dating and are just using me. he begged me to stop because he knew the truth
column5: he knows how his friends were using it and how he used to and that it really is not safe for me because i was taking it seriously.

column1: i went on so many dates over the years and the best thing i got from online dating was my therapist
column2: who i got as a recommendation from one of the last guys i dated. he helped me break the online dating addiction! it might sound silly to say addiction but i was totally addicted because of the fear of being alone
column3: ending up the girl who is a loser and lives alone with no love in her life. this fear kept me dating for far too long. turns out there is nothing wrong with me and i feel more love than ever before despite still being single. don't believe the nonsense that you must be in a relationship or dating to be satisfied and happy with your life! it's wonderful to be free from the pressure i had put on myself

column1: and it's taken me years to be able to look at myself and see beauty. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

column1: 106884;instagram;2018-12-19 14:20:04;FALSE;"it's been almost a week since i watched luca guadagnino's 'suspiria'; i'm still simultaneously fascinated and apalled and i can't yet explain why! the film transports the narration to germany in the 1970s (the exact time in which the original suspiria by dario argento was released) but the historical context that was only hinted in argento's classic is made fully palpable in this remake: the reverberations of nazism
column2: the berlin wall and the red army faction. this political atmosphere shrouds and interacts with a story about female power
column4: whose cryptic and horrifying scenes are as difficult to decipher as to forget. after a first watching
column5: i get the feeling of having watched the dark flip side of the #metoo movement reimagined in the guise of a historically silenced sorority and matriarchy who have held power in shadows. definitely

column1: hace casi una semana que vi 'suspiria' de luca guadagnino; aún estoy fascinado y horrorizado a la vez y ¡no sé explicar por qué! la película transporta la narración a alemania en los años 70 (justo la época en la que se estrenó el original de dario argento) pero el contexto histórico que sólo se intuía en el clásico de argento se hace totalmente tangible en este remake: los ecos del nazismo
column2: el muro de berlín y la facción roja. esta atmósfera política envuelve e interactúa con una historia sobre poder femenino
column4: cuyas escenas crípticas y terroríficas son tan difíciles de descifrar como de olvidar. tras un primer visionado
column5: esta película se me antoja como el reverso tenebroso del movimiento #metoo reimaginado bajo el disfraz de una sororidad y matriarcado silenciados que han ejercido el poder en la sombra. definitivamente
column6: ¡esta película hay que verla más de una vez!

column1: 106919;instagram;2018-12-19 13:10:43;FALSE;i posted this pic on yesterday.... then i thought about when i was growing up... my dad loved farming ( i didn’t get that bug)... he would plant and wait for the crops to grow. when it was time to harvest the fruit of his labor- he
column2: my brother and mother went to work. (my brother jokes me because he asks what do i know about harvesting bc i never worked in the garden😂)... i do know
column3: they would get up early and work until dark to pull in the harvest. after it was taken from the garden my mom would can or freeze what was brought in. so often we hear “its harvest time “.. and we get excited... and yes we should... however i think we forget that the blessings are great! just like my parents loved seeing those vegetables (the blessings) in the garden
column4: they also knew it was going to take work to bring in the harvest. there is no room in the kingdom for laziness....if we allow god given opportunities to pass us by because they look too much like work
column5: then shame on us.  matthew 9:37 “the harvest is plentiful but the workers are few”... don’t allow blessings dressed in work clothes pass you by! have a fantastic day!!!! #metoo #letsgettowork;;en;#metoo

column1: 今日で中級クラス最後のレッスンでした✩
９月からクラスを持たせてもらって
10月にはいきなり発表会があって１ヶ月ない中で
作品作ってみんな覚えてくれて無事発表会も終わり
あっという間に12月になって今年最後のレッスン。
最初どんなジャンルなのかも分からずに
受けてくれて今もそのまま受けてくれていて
子供達からも親御さんからも「楽しい！」って
言って頂きそのお陰で今頑張れてます😊❤️
色んなジャンルをしてみんな自分の好きなジャンルを
見つけてもらえたらな〜と思いながら
レッスンしてて少しでもそれがこれから
伝わっていくようなレッスンに出来たらなと🥰
そして今日は遊びながら前々から作ってた
振りで今年締めくくり最後の1×8はチームを作って
そのチームの子達で和気あいあいと振りを
